nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nRetrieval: opened by web fetch on 2026-06-30; readable article lines 116-166.\\n\\nRelevant extracted text:\\n\\nHeadline/subhead: \\\"Clavicular's bizarre 'pregnancy contest' claim sparks backlash on social media; 'I will be a dad...'\\\" The subhead says: \\\"Live streamer Braden Peters, aka Clavicular, sparked outrage after proposing a contest for 500 women to become impregnated by him.\\\"\\n\\nArticle body identifies Clavicular as streamer Braden Peters and describes the issue as an on-stream suggestion. Under \\\"What Was The Contest?\\\" it reports: \\\"In a recent live show, the streamer suggested a contest where 500 women would take part in a beauty pageant type contest with the victory becoming impregnated by him.\\\"\\n\\nThe article quotes the stream language as: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today,\\\" and says Peters then said, \\\"I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n\\nThe article states the video went viral and drew a swift negative response. It compares the reaction to another creator's fake pregnancy rage-bait episode and reports that people online criticized Peters and the contest idea. The article frames the remarks as a proposed impregnation contest and possible joke/shock content, not as confirmation that Clavicular and a current partner were already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nLimitations: This is secondary reporting and does not preserve the original livestream video or a complete transcript.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S4 Express Tribune contest context\\nTitle: Clavicular's 'pregnancy contest' claim sparks backlash after controversial live-stream comments\\nSource: The Express Tribune / Pop Culture \\u0026 Art\\nPublished: April 25, 2026\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nRetrieval: opened by web fetch on 2026-06-30; readable article lines 21-47.\\n\\nRelevant extracted text:\\n\\nHeadline/subhead: \\\"Clavicular's 'pregnancy contest' claim sparks backlash after controversial live-stream comments\\\" and \\\"Braden Peters suggested a competition involving around 500 women, where the winner would be impregnated by him.\\\"\\n\\nArticle body: \\\"Streamer Braden Peters, known online as Clavicular, is facing intense backlash after proposing a controversial 'pregnancy contest' during a livestream that quickly went viral.\\\"\\n\\nIt reports: \\\"According to reports, Peters suggested organising a competition involving around 500 women, structured like a beauty pageant, where the winner would be impregnated by him. He claimed the idea was part of his desire to become a father soon, saying he wanted to have children 'within the next couple months.'\\\"\\n\\nIt quotes the reported stream language: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today,\\\" and \\\"I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n\\nThe article says critics argued that even if intended as a joke or shock content, the idea normalized harmful attitudes. It adds that the controversy was fueled by Clavicular's history of viral stunts and provocative content and that observers questioned whether the statement was serious or designed purely for engagement.\\n\\nThe article concludes: \\\"Clavicular has not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical, leaving ongoing debate about the boundaries between online shock content and real-world implications.\\\"\\n\\nLimitations: This is secondary reporting and does not preserve the original livestream video or a complete transcript.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Forbes article extracted relevant text - Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute (ev_2c388df14c13_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-2c388df14c13)\\nSource: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nSHA-256: `2c388df14c13d9b9467639a7d55ed1032f734feda3511558f407f13b5313ca19`\\nBytes: 1913\\nRelevance: Contains credible media reporting about the disputed Clavicular pregnancy market, including plaintiff-favorable characterization of the underlying alleged statement and adverse clarification context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Polymarket Gamma API event capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026 (ev_b08e7634a0e9_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b08e7634a0e9)\\nSource: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nSHA-256: `b08e7634a0e9ffce034aee5bcd9d0438eb0db8944881a9043d3eff41276e0a89`\\nBytes: 3710\\nRelevance: Primary platform API record showing market wording, final Yes outcome, resolution status, creation/closed times, volume, and Polymarket event metadata context.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Times of India fact check - Clavicular pregnancy rumor (ev_c3000953fc81_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c3000953fc81)\\nSource: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nSHA-256: `c3000953fc81ce56286e160abe46babc7a362a6ca6eccf04b04912589971fec0`\\nBytes: 2281\\nRelevance: Adverse source testing whether the alleged Clavicular pregnancy announcement was credible or instead an unsupported viral rumor mixed with contest/joke remarks.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Hindustan Times article - Clavicular pregnancy contest remarks (ev_519a3b6f458c_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-519a3b6f458c)\\nSource: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nSHA-256: `519a3b6f458ce0062d93adc355c77e68462d7cc1ffee76fa7667401d2c703272`\\nBytes: 1779\\nRelevance: Adverse source showing the reported Clavicular livestream remarks concerned a proposed pregnancy contest and future desire to be a father, not confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Express Tribune article - Clavicular pregnancy contest and lack of clarification (ev_115037a41d09_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-115037a41d09)\\nSource: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nSHA-256: `115037a41d09da8800a81a03e18062f238099cfe6bf699277c130fcd3885eab8`\\nBytes: 2006\\nRelevance: Corroborates defense characterization that the preserved public reporting describes a proposed pregnancy contest and future fatherhood remarks, with no clarification whether genuine or satirical, rather than a confirmed partner pregnancy announcement.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and search ledger\\nRefreshed the case record and evidence list before filing. Read the packet files during opening; in argument phase, searched targeted public sources from the packet. Fetched the official Polymarket Gamma API by curl and submitted the resulting platform JSON. Fetched Forbes by curl with a browser user-agent; the page was metered/paywalled, but HTML/Next.js payload exposed article metadata and relevant fragments, which were submitted with limitations noted. Opened Times of India through web fetch and submitted the readable adverse article text. Could not preserve the original Clavicular VOD/clip/transcript in this turn; that remains the main source-chain gap and is accounted for in the merits argument.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-chain search ledger\\nReviewed current record and read plaintiff's new Forbes, Gamma API, and Times of India submissions through AAR read_evidence_range. Conducted targeted web fetches of Hindustan Times and The Express Tribune articles identified in the packet; both rendered readable relevant text and were submitted as defense evidence. Tried direct web access to the Domahhhh X thread and fxtwitter/vxtwitter variants, but no usable source text was retrieved, so it is not relied on as evidence. Remaining material gaps are original Clavicular VOD/clip/transcript, full Forbes source chain, Polymarket clarification said to say No, and UMA transaction-level records.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T07:06:08.640091694Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":890292,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":13},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":18,\"version\":29}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C5","after_version":29,"case_id":"arb-ex09-20260630062717","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C5","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C5\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is about a narrow factual proposition, not whether Polymarket's early resolution process was ideal: between April 20, 2026 and December 31, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, did Clavicular make a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy?\n\nThe current packet already establishes the governing rule and the real dispute. The Polymarket market-page record preserves the operative language: the announcement must be by Clavicular, must concern him and a partner expecting a baby through pregnancy, must occur in the stated window, and must be credible; jokes or other non-credible pregnancy announcements do not qualify. That same official-source material records the market as finally resolved Yes after proposal and dispute rounds. The final market state is not conclusive by itself, but it is important context: the live oracle process reached the same factual side plaintiff advances.\n\nThe strongest current plaintiff evidence is the secondary reporting packet. Forbes described the disputed market as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description, if supported by the underlying statement or by a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, matches the rule's core: an announcement from Clavicular concerning a pregnancy with a partner. The market rule expressly allows credible-media consensus as a possible resolution source, so the case does not fail merely because a council later receives the proof through media reporting rather than a preserved livestream file.\n\nBut the packet is candid about what it does not yet prove. It does not contain the original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, or complete source chain. It also contains adverse reporting: Times of India says no video or Clavicular statement confirmed a pregnancy, and other reports frame the available remarks as a controversial pregnancy-contest proposal or shock-content performance. Those materials matter because the rule excludes jokes and non-credible claims. A statement like wanting children soon, standing alone, would not satisfy the proposition; neither would a rumor about a girlfriend if Clavicular did not credibly announce it.\n\nSo the decisive question is not whether there was internet chatter about Clavicular and pregnancy. There plainly was. The decisive question is whether the best source material shows a credible announcement of an existing expected baby through pregnancy, rather than a hypothetical contest, satire, or unconfirmed rumor. Plaintiff's burden is only preponderance. The final Yes resolution, the official rule allowing credible media consensus, and Forbes's direct characterization give plaintiff a concrete path to meeting that burden. The defense path is also visible: show that the only preserved statements were jokes, hypotheticals, or reports explicitly denying confirmation.\n\nIn the evidence phases, the council should expect the case to turn on source-chain proof: the original stream or clip if it can be preserved; the Forbes article and its cited sources; the platform clarification Forbes references; the Domahhhh thread and related X posts only to the extent they reveal source material rather than trader opinion; and the adverse fact-checks or later clarifications. If that source chain confirms that Clavicular told his audience he had gotten a partner/girlfriend pregnant, plaintiff should prevail. If it shows only a pregnancy-contest stunt or unsupported rumor, plaintiff should not. On the current packet, plaintiff's theory is that the Yes resolution and Forbes reporting point to a qualifying announcement, and the remaining proceedings should test that source chain rather than treat the missing original clip as the end of the inquiry.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense position is simple: this market did not ask whether Polymarket eventually paid Yes, whether traders argued about Clavicular, or whether the internet repeated a pregnancy rumor. It asked whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. On the current admitted record, that decisive fact remains unproved.\n\nThe market-page record is important, but it helps define the burden more than it satisfies it. It preserves the rule: a qualifying announcement must be credible; jokes and non-credible pregnancy announcements do not suffice; and the source should be statements from Clavicular or representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting only as a possible substitute. That same file records a final Yes resolution after proposal and dispute rounds. The defense does not ignore that. But a final platform state is not the announcement itself, and the case packet does not preserve the source chain that would let the council test whether the final state tracked the rule.\n\nThe packet's own primary-evidence file makes that distinction explicit. The preserved primary/platform material proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The official-source record likewise says no primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in the packet. That is not a technical quibble. It is the core missing link, because the difference between a qualifying announcement and a non-qualifying stunt depends on exact words, context, speaker, timing, and credibility.\n\nThe secondary reporting is conflicted. Forbes is the strongest current support for plaintiff because it characterizes the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. If a reliable source chain ultimately confirms that statement, in context, as a serious announcement about Clavicular and a partner expecting a baby through pregnancy, plaintiff may have a case. But the same admitted secondary-reporting file contains substantial contrary material. Times of India is summarized as saying there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no video confirming pregnancy, and no Clavicular statement confirming it. Hindustan Times and the Express Tribune are summarized as describing a controversial pregnancy-contest proposal or shock-content remarks about wanting children and being a dad in the next few months, not confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\nThat conflict matters because the rule excludes non-credible announcements, and because the proposition requires “he and a partner” expecting a baby through pregnancy. A statement of aspiration, a proposed contest, a joke, a viral inference, or a trader's interpretation is not enough. Nor is a report about internet backlash enough unless it traces back to a preserved statement or a genuine consensus of credible reporting on the specific proposition.\n\nBefore this opening, defense reviewed the packet and ran targeted source searches to identify what should be tested in the evidence phase. The same gaps remain the decisive ones: the original livestream clip or VOD, a transcript or faithful excerpt, the Forbes source chain, the referenced Polymarket clarification, the Domahhhh thread and any embedded source material, and the UMA/proposer/disputer records if they explain what evidence the oracle actually relied on. Opening rules do not allow us to admit those materials now, but the council should understand why they matter.\n\nSo the defense opening is not that plaintiff can never prove the proposition. It is that the admitted record presently does not carry plaintiff's burden. It proves a market rule, a final Yes outcome, and a noisy dispute. It also proves missing primary evidence, unresolved source-chain problems, and adverse reporting that frames the relevant statements as non-confirming or non-credible. In the evidence phases, plaintiff should be required to produce the actual statement or a reliable captured chain showing a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. If the record remains where it is now, the proposition should be rejected.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, not perfect preservation. The record now shows that the more likely factual answer is Yes, while also showing exactly why the question was disputed.\n\nFirst, the governing rule is undisputed. The market-page and official-source records say this market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy in the window; jokes and non-credible announcements do not count; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the primary resolution source, but a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered. The Gamma API capture confirms the same rule, final outcome prices of Yes 1 / No 0, a resolved status, and closure on May 1, 2026. That does not itself prove the announcement, but it is primary platform evidence that the live market/oracle process reached Yes under that rule.\n\nSecond, the best admitted media evidence points to a qualifying statement. The case-packet secondary-reporting file says Forbes summarized the dispute as being over “what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement” from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The newly admitted Forbes extraction corroborates the source, date, author, article identity, market volume, Yes price, and the article-payload fragment “gotten a girl pregnant,” immediately tied to the rule excluding non-credible announcements. A statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant is not merely an aspiration to have children someday. In ordinary usage it announces an existing pregnancy involving Clavicular and a partner. Under the market rule, credible media reporting may be considered; here Forbes is a mainstream financial outlet reporting on the exact disputed market, not a random social repost.\n\nThird, the official platform context is consistent with that Yes-side evaluation. The Gamma API event metadata says trader consensus locked in a 99.9% Yes probability for Clavicular’s pregnancy announcement, with large volume and a final Yes outcome. It also says the narrative involved repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama contest pitch, and viral backlash. That context is mixed, but it explains why the market could treat the matter as a Clavicular announcement dispute rather than a baseless rumor floating in isolation.\n\nThe defense’s strongest point is real: the original stream or full transcript is still missing. Plaintiff does not ask the council to ignore that. The unresolved-gaps file and primary-evidence file both say the packet lacks the VOD/clip/transcript and that original source material would be best. That affects weight. It does not erase the admitted Forbes reporting, the final platform Yes resolution, or the rule’s allowance for credible-media consensus.\n\nThe Times of India fact-check is also important, but it does not defeat plaintiff on this record. TOI says the viral claim about a girlfriend after 10 days lacked proof, and it treats the “I must have children” / “I will be a dad” language as a pregnancy-contest or out-of-context clip. If the only evidence were those remarks, plaintiff would lose. But Forbes reported the dispute differently: as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The council must weigh conflicting secondary sources. Forbes is focused on the Polymarket/UMA dispute and the market rule; TOI is focused on debunking a viral social-media rumor and does not purport to reconstruct the oracle evidence.\n\nSo what does the evidence prove? It proves the market asked exactly this factual question; it proves the official platform ended in Yes; it proves credible-media reporting, especially Forbes, described a direct pregnancy claim; and it proves there were contrary accounts casting related clips as jokes, contest talk, or unconfirmed rumor. What it does not prove is the exact original wording from a preserved VOD. That missing link prevents a slam dunk, but preponderance still favors plaintiff because the best market-specific evidence and the actual resolved platform record align on Yes.\n\nThe provenance limits are transparent. PX-6 is a partial Forbes extraction from a metered page, not a full article capture. PX-7 is a primary API capture and strong for market state but mixed on underlying facts. PX-8 is adverse and credible enough to weigh against us. Taken together with the packet, the more probable explanation is that Clavicular made a direct, public, market-moving pregnancy announcement that Forbes and the oracle treated as qualifying, while later fact-checks disputed less precise viral retellings. On a preponderance standard, the proposition should be found true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried even a preponderance burden on the actual proposition. The proposition is not “did Polymarket resolve Yes?” or “did people discuss a pregnancy rumor?” It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\nStart with what is proven. D-1/PX-1 proves the rule and the final Yes platform state. D-2 and D-3 prove the source-chain problem: the record lacks the original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA transaction-level records. D-2 says the preserved primary/platform material proves contract wording and final platform state, but not that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. That is the decisive gap.\n\nPlaintiff’s new evidence does not close it. PX-6, the Forbes item, is not a full article or primary source. It is a partial extraction from a metered page, and its own limitation says it captured snippets from a rendered/serialized payload, not the original Clavicular stream, VOD, or transcript. The helpful fragment is “gotten a girl pregnant.” But without the surrounding sentence, source, clip, speaker context, and credibility assessment, that fragment cannot establish the required elements. It could be Forbes summarizing a disputed claim, a joke, or the very rumor that the rule excludes. The same Forbes extraction also says the market description and platform clarification said No, while price said Yes. That weakens, rather than strengthens, reliance on price or oracle outcome as proof of fact.\n\nPX-7, the Gamma API, is likewise not evidence of the announcement. It is evidence of market metadata and final prices. Its event metadata actually supports defense ambiguity: it describes repeated vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show or baby-mama contest pitch, viral backlash, and debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend’s pregnancy after 10 days. Those are not the same thing as a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby.\n\nThe sources that preserve actual reported words point away from the proposition. D-4/PX-8, the Times of India fact check, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no video confirming pregnancy, and no statement from Clavicular confirming it. It says the viral claim came from a Kick Champ post and that the shared clip was out of context; what people actually found was a separate “pregnancy contest” remark: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” That language is future-oriented aspiration or shock content, not a present pregnancy announcement with a partner.\n\nD-5, Hindustan Times, independently describes the same event as a contest where 500 women would participate and the winner would become impregnated by him. It quotes the same desire/future-fatherhood language and frames the event as backlash to a troubling on-stream suggestion. D-6, The Express Tribune, corroborates that framing: a proposed pregnancy contest, a desire to have children within the next couple months, possible joke or shock content, and no clarification whether the proposal was genuine or satirical.\n\nOn credibility, this record is not balanced at 50.1% for plaintiff. The rule expressly excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes. The admitted evidence containing fuller context identifies a rumor, no confirmation, no video proof, a contest proposal, and possible shock content. Plaintiff asks the council to infer a qualifying announcement from an incomplete Forbes fragment plus a final market state. But the final market state is exactly what was disputed, and the Forbes fragment is exactly what needs the missing source chain.\n\nWhat the record proves: rule text, market final Yes, major trading volume, internet controversy, and conflicting secondary accounts. What it does not prove: the original wording, a preserved Clavicular or representative statement, the existence of a partner, or that any announcement was credible rather than a joke, stunt, rumor, or future plan.\n\nA preponderance finding requires the more likely factual conclusion. Here the more likely conclusion from the admitted evidence is that Clavicular made provocative remarks about wanting children and a pregnancy contest, while a separate viral claim about a girlfriend pregnancy went unconfirmed. Because plaintiff has not shown a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy, the council should find the proposition false.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. If the only record were the “pregnancy contest” remarks, plaintiff would not have carried the burden. But the record is not limited to those remarks, and the defense’s new articles do not rebut the separate Forbes-reported pregnancy statement.\n\nThe defense treats all sources as describing the same event. They do not. Times of India, Hindustan Times, and The Express Tribune focus on a backlash story: Clavicular talked about wanting children, a contest involving many women, and becoming a dad in the next few months. Those reports are useful adverse context, and plaintiff admitted TOI for that reason. But they show that one category of public remarks may be non-qualifying; they do not prove there was no other qualifying statement. The Forbes packet and Forbes extraction address the exact Polymarket/UMA dispute and preserve the key characterization that the controversy involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is materially different from “I want children” or a proposed contest.\n\nThe defense also overstates the effect of the missing VOD. The rule does not require the council to possess the original stream or a representative statement in every case. It expressly says a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered. That matters because markets like this are often resolved from public reporting where original livestreams, clips, or deleted posts are not cleanly preserved. The missing VOD reduces confidence; it does not make credible media evidence legally irrelevant.\n\nNor does the Forbes adverse fragment prove No. “Market description and platform clarification say No; price says Yes; oracle...has not closed the gap” shows a dispute existed. It does not establish the platform clarification was correct, and it predates or describes the very conflict that ultimately ended in a final Yes state. The Gamma API shows the market resolved Yes with outcome prices Yes 1 / No 0 after proposal and dispute rounds. That is not just “price”; it is primary platform evidence of final resolution under this rule.\n\nThe defense says the fuller-context articles “preserve actual reported words.” They preserve actual words for the contest/future-fatherhood remarks, not for the Forbes-described “gotten a girl pregnant” statement. That distinction is the whole case. The council should not let adverse evidence about a non-qualifying category swallow separate market-specific evidence about a qualifying category.\n\nSo the correct weighing is this: plaintiff has imperfect but market-specific evidence of a direct pregnancy announcement, supported by Forbes and final platform resolution; defense has credible evidence that related viral contest/future-fatherhood clips were non-confirming. Under preponderance, the question is which account more likely explains the final Yes market-specific dispute. Plaintiff’s account still does: Forbes’s direct pregnancy characterization and the resolved Gamma record are more probative of the actual Polymarket proposition than later backlash articles about an adjacent contest controversy. The proposition should be found true.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal identifies the central issue correctly: if there were a separate, direct, credible Clavicular statement that he had gotten a partner pregnant, that would be materially different from contest and future-fatherhood remarks. But plaintiff still has not proven that separate statement.\n\nThe record does not contain the supposed separate source. It contains a partial Forbes extraction with a fragment, not the original livestream, not a transcript, not a full clean Forbes article body, not the surrounding sentence, not the embedded source chain, not the platform clarification, and not the UMA records. Plaintiff’s rebuttal asks the council to treat the missing source as if it exists because Forbes may have been referring to it. That reverses the burden. Defense does not have to disprove every unpreserved possible statement; plaintiff has to show the qualifying statement is more likely than not.\n\nThe rule’s media-consensus clause does not solve that problem. It permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. This record has the opposite: conflicting media. The fuller admitted sources that preserve actual reported words describe desire to have children, a proposed pregnancy contest, possible joke or shock content, and no clarification whether genuine or satirical. The Times of India fact check goes further: no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no video confirming pregnancy, and no Clavicular statement confirming it.\n\nPlaintiff says those sources address a different category. Perhaps. But that only proves the gap. The only category actually preserved with context is non-qualifying. The allegedly qualifying category is represented by an incomplete Forbes fragment and a final market state. A final Yes resolution is evidence that the platform resolved Yes; it is not independent proof that the factual predicate happened. The Forbes extraction itself reports that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, which shows why the oracle result cannot be treated as a clean proxy for truth.\n\nOn preponderance, the council must choose the more likely factual conclusion from admitted evidence, not from an assumed missing clip. The more likely conclusion remains that Clavicular made provocative, non-confirming remarks about wanting children and a pregnancy contest, while a viral girlfriend-pregnancy claim remained unverified. Because the record still lacks a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy, the proposition should be found false.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition should be found true on a preponderance of the evidence.\n\nThe question is narrow: did Clavicular make a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the window? The rule itself supplies the key evidentiary standard: statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, but a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered. That language matters. It means the council should not demand perfect preservation of the original livestream as the only possible proof. The missing VOD is important; it is not automatically fatal.\n\nThe strongest evidence for plaintiff is market-specific. The official market record and Gamma API establish the exact rule, the creation window, and the final Yes resolution after proposal and dispute rounds. The Forbes packet and admitted Forbes extraction then supply the factual link: Forbes covered this exact Polymarket/UMA dispute and described it as turning on a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That statement, if credited, satisfies the proposition in ordinary language. It is not merely future aspiration, not merely “I want children,” and not merely a contest proposal.\n\nThe defense evidence deserves weight, but it answers a different question. Times of India, Hindustan Times, and The Express Tribune show that one set of public remarks involved a pregnancy contest, wanting children, and becoming a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff has never asked you to treat those remarks alone as sufficient. They are adverse because they show why this market was disputed and why “credible” matters. But they do not disprove the separate market-specific report that Clavicular told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant.\n\nThe defense’s closing theme is absence: no original stream, no full transcript, no full clean Forbes body, no Polymarket clarification, no UMA records. Those gaps are real. But preponderance asks what is more likely on this record, not whether every ideal source was preserved. The record contains one source tied directly to the market dispute and the asserted direct pregnancy claim: Forbes. It also contains primary platform evidence that the market ultimately resolved Yes under a rule that excluded jokes and non-credible announcements. Against that, the defense has credible evidence about adjacent non-confirming contest remarks and a fact-check of viral girlfriend-pregnancy rumors, but no primary denial, no preserved platform clarification, and no source proving that Forbes’s “gotten a girl pregnant” account was merely the same contest remark.\n\nThat is the decisive distinction. If the council collapses the Forbes-reported pregnancy statement into the contest remarks, defendant wins. But the admitted record does not require that collapse. It shows conflicting public narratives: a non-qualifying contest/backlash narrative, and a market-specific qualifying-statement narrative. Because the Polymarket rule permits credible media reporting, because Forbes addressed the exact market dispute, and because the final official platform record resolved Yes after disputes, the qualifying-statement narrative is more likely than not.\n\nSo plaintiff’s position is candid and limited: the case is not perfect; the missing original clip reduces confidence; the adverse sources prevent certainty. But the standard is preponderance. The better reading of the record is that Clavicular made a public, market-moving announcement that he had gotten a girl/partner pregnant, and that the subsequent dispute arose because others characterized adjacent remarks as jokes, contest talk, or rumor. On this record, the Yes side has the greater weight. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the proposition should be found false because plaintiff has not proved the required announcement by a preponderance.\n\nThe rule is precise. It requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy. It excludes jokes and non-credible pregnancy announcements. It permits statements from Clavicular or representatives, and may consider a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The record must therefore prove more than a market price, a final resolution, or internet controversy. It must prove the qualifying announcement.\n\nThe record does not do that. The primary/platform evidence proves the market wording and final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying factual predicate. The case-packet primary-evidence file says exactly that. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the missing materials that would decide the case: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA records. Those gaps are not cosmetic. This case turns on exact words and context because “credible” is the disputed term.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is Forbes. If the record contained a full article with a source chain, or if several credible sources converged on the same direct Clavicular statement, plaintiff might meet the burden despite the missing VOD. But the admitted Forbes item is a partial extraction from a metered page. Its own limitation says it preserves snippets from a serialized payload, not a full clean article body and not the original stream, VOD, or transcript. The favorable fragment, “gotten a girl pregnant,” is not enough without context to decide whether Forbes was reporting a confirmed statement, summarizing a disputed rumor, or describing a joke or non-credible claim. The same Forbes exhibit also preserves an adverse point: the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes.\n\nThe Gamma API likewise cannot carry the burden. It proves final Yes and market metadata. Its narrative context actually highlights why the matter was not a clean pregnancy announcement: public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show or baby-mama contest pitch, viral backlash, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. That is not a preserved Clavicular statement that he and a partner were expecting a baby.\n\nThe fuller admitted reporting points the other way. Times of India says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no video confirming pregnancy, and no Clavicular statement confirming it. Hindustan Times and The Express Tribune preserve the actual reported words: wanting children, getting children today, becoming a dad in the next few months, and a contest involving hundreds of women. Those words may be provocative; they may be ugly; they may be market-moving. They are not a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\n\nPlaintiff’s closing asks you not to collapse the Forbes-reported statement into the contest remarks. But the problem is that the separate Forbes-reported statement is not actually preserved. Plaintiff bears the burden to prove it, not merely to posit it. The media-consensus clause does not mean one incomplete fragment defeats three adverse source captures and the packet’s own source-chain warnings. A “definitive consensus” is absent; the admitted media conflict is the record.\n\nSo the decisive weighing is this: on plaintiff’s side, final platform Yes plus an incomplete Forbes fragment. On defense’s side, admitted primary-source gaps, no preserved Clavicular statement, no preserved transcript, an adverse platform-clarification fragment, a fact check finding no confirmation, and two additional reports tying the actual quoted remarks to a contest or future-fatherhood stunt. That is not 50.1% for plaintiff.\n\nThe council should decide the proposition on the evidence actually admitted. That evidence shows controversy and an early Yes resolution, but it does not show a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Find the proposition false.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page rule and final Yes record\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\n\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRule text:\n\n> This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n>\n> Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n>\n> The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\n\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\n\nEvent:\n\n- event id: 400878\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: true\n- event closed: true\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\n\nMarket:\n\n- market id: 2037907\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\n- market closed: true\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"1\", \"0\"]\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source record and source-chain notes\n# Official source record\n\n## Polymarket source\n\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\n\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\n\n## Clavicular or representative statements\n\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\n\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\n\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\n\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\n\n## UMA / oracle source\n\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Primary/platform evidence assessment\n# Primary evidence\n\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\n\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\n\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\n\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\n\n## Preliminary source assessment\n\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Secondary reporting packet\n# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Unresolved record gaps\n# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-6 Forbes extracted article fragments\nRetrieval/extraction notes: curl -L -A 'Mozilla/5.0' fetched the Forbes page. Grep over the HTML/Next.js payload for Clavicular/pregnant/market description terms returned the following relevant page text fragments and metadata.\n\nSource metadata:\n- Title: \"Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\" / \"'Inmates Taking The Asylum'--Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet\"\n- Author: Boaz Sobrado\n- Publisher: Forbes Digital Assets\n- Published/modified: 2026-04-30T17:55:56-04:00\n- URL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\n- Structured metadata description: \"Polymarket's $16M Clavicular pregnancy bet is testing UMA's oracle as top traders call the resolution layer 'a disinformation engine taken over by rogue traders.'\"\n- Page metadata says isAccessibleForFree: False.\n\nExtracted relevant fragments from article payload:\n- The disputed market, linked as \"Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\", had done $16.46 million in lifetime volume on Polymarket, including roughly $4.5 million in the past 24 hours, and Yes shares traded at 97 cents.\n- Fragment: \"gotten a girl pregnant. The market's own rules state that 'pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.' Other traders posting through the dispute, including @holy_mos...\"\n- Fragment: \"market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.\"\n- Fragment: \"Clavicular pregnancy at 99.7 cents,\" @JexTrade posted late on April 29. \"Is UMA gonna rug the whales on this next vote?\"\n\nLimitations: The extraction captured snippets from Forbes's rendered/serialized article payload, not a full clean article body. It supports source-chain targeting and shows Forbes's characterization, but it does not itself preserve the original Clavicular stream, VOD, or transcript.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-7 Polymarket Gamma API capture\n[{\"id\":\"400878\",\"ticker\":\"clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"slug\":\"clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"title\":\"Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\",\"description\":\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.  \\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\",\"resolutionSource\":\"\",\"startDate\":\"2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\",\"creationDate\":\"2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\",\"endDate\":\"2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\",\"active\":true,\"closed\":true,\"archived\":false,\"volume\":13934862.960998023,\"openInterest\":5749723.168803,\"createdAt\":\"2026-04-20T22:28:47.730186Z\",\"updatedAt\":\"2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z\",\"commentCount\":1124,\"markets\":[{\"id\":\"2037907\",\"question\":\"Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\",\"conditionId\":\"0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\",\"slug\":\"clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"endDate\":\"2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\",\"startDate\":\"2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\",\"description\":\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.  \\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\",\"outcomes\":\"[\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\",\"outcomePrices\":\"[\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\",\"volume\":\"13934862.960998023\",\"active\":true,\"closed\":true,\"createdAt\":\"2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\",\"updatedAt\":\"2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z\",\"closedTime\":\"2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\",\"resolvedBy\":\"0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\",\"questionID\":\"0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\",\"umaEndDate\":\"2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\",\"umaResolutionStatus\":\"resolved\",\"lastTradePrice\":0.999,\"bestBid\":0.998,\"bestAsk\":0.999,\"automaticallyResolved\":true,\"umaResolutionStatuses\":\"[\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\"}],\"closedTime\":\"2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\",\"eventMetadata\":{\"context_description\":\"Trader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants. Recent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31. Realistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\",\"context_requires_regen\":true,\"context_updated_at\":\"2026-05-01T00:31:22.155Z\"}}]\n\n[plaintiff] PX-8 Times of India adverse fact-check\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nAuthor/source line: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST\n\nRelevant extracted text from fetched page:\n\nClavicular is trending again, and this time it is about a rumor that spread very fast online. The 20-year-old streamer, whose real name is Braden Peters, was suddenly at the center of claims that he is expecting his first child. The story sounded shocking, people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her. The claim picked up millions of views and quickly moved across social media. Many users were confused.\n\nSome even believed it at first because Clavicular had recently said he wants to become a father soon. But when people looked closely, things did not add up. There was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update. At the same time, Clavicular has been dealing with serious real-life issues. He was recently hospitalized after collapsing during a livestream. His publicist also left him, saying he needs to take his health more seriously.\n\nThe rumor started from a viral post on Kick Champ that crossed over 13 million views. It claimed Clavicular was \"expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.\" The post also said he broke down emotionally after hearing the news. But there is no real proof behind this claim. No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either. What people actually found is that the clip being shared was taken out of context. In that video, he does not react to baby news. Instead, he looks tired and unwell. The confusion seems to come from something else he said earlier on livestream.\n\nStreamer Clavicular talked about a strange idea, a \"pregnancy contest.\" He told viewers he wanted to have a child soon and even suggested a contest involving hundreds of women. His exact words were: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n\nThe article concludes that right now there is no confirmed pregnancy and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.\n\n[defendant] D-1 Market rule and final platform state\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\n\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRule text:\n\n> This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n>\n> Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n>\n> The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\n\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\n\nEvent:\n\n- event id: 400878\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: true\n- event closed: true\n- event